The cost of a colour TV licence in the UK is £159, so getting a free licence could make a big difference to pensioners who are currently feeling a financial squeeze. Claimants of Pension Credit could get their licence for free. To claim a free licence, an individual must be aged 75 or over. Those who live with someone who receives Pension Credit could also claim a free licence. The licence covers everyone living at an address. People who already get Pension Credit can start their application when they are 74. READ MORE: NS&I announces Premium Bonds jackpot winners for April 2022 - how to check if you won They will still have to pay for their licence until they actually turn 75, but then they will immediately be covered by a free licence. Britons can apply for a free licence online through the TV Licensing website. They can also apply by phone on 0300 790 6071. DON'T MISSState pension: Six increases will take place from next month - will you get more? [ALERT]Can you still submit your meter reading today? What to do if you couldn't do it yesterday [INSIGHT]Octopus Energy CEO says meter readings causing ‘unnecessary stress’ and offers his advice [WARNING] Pension Credit is a benefit paid to pensioners on lower incomes by the Department for Work and Pensions (DWP). It is paid at two different rates depending on one’s circumstances. Guarantee Credit, the core element of Pension Credit, tops up single pensioners’ income to £177.10 and those with a partner to £270.30. Savings Credit, which is only available to those who reached state pension age before April 6, 2016, pays out up to £14.04 a week to single pensioners and £15.71 to couples. From April 11, 2022, the rates of both Guarantee Credit and Savings Credit will increase. Guarantee Credit recipients will get up to £182.60 if they are single or £278.70 if they have a partner. Savings Credit will pay out up to £14.48 to single claimants and £16.20 to couples. Claimants of Pension Credit can also get other help, such as: